      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While many international legal bodies lean toward the Western interpretation of UNCLOS, proponents of historical claims argue that long-standing usage and administrative control establish a legitimate right to the territory. They contend that international law must also incorporate customary rights that develop over time, not just modern treaties. However, the current legal framework heavily favors maritime boundaries defined by international conventions, which often clash with vague historical assertions. Ultimately, the dispute remains a political and legal battleground where different interpretations of \"validity\" compete.",
      "source": "target",
